# Cursor Rules — L&D Framework Builder

You are helping build a Next.js 14 (App Router) + TypeScript app with two AI
tools: a Competency BARS generator and a Learning Objective & Micro-Assessment
builder. Both share a provider-agnostic LLM layer.

## Golden rules

- NEVER hardcode API keys or secrets. Read them from environment variables at
  request time. `.env.local` is git-ignored.
- NEVER expose the API key to the browser. All LLM calls run server-side inside
  `app/api/**/route.ts`.
- ALWAYS validate and sanitise user input before sending it to the model
  (see `lib/bars/validation.ts`, `lib/objectives/validation.ts`).
- Keep AI-independent logic (validation, prompt building, response parsing) as
  PURE functions in `lib/` so they can be unit-tested without the network.
- The only file allowed to make network calls is `lib/llm.ts`.
- Mirror the existing structure: each tool has its own
  `validation.ts` / `prompt.ts` / `parse.ts` under `lib/<tool>/` plus a route
  under `app/api/<tool>/`.

## Code style

- TypeScript strict mode. Prefer explicit types on exported functions.
- Small, single-purpose functions. Thin API routes.
- Handle errors gracefully: return a user-safe message, log details server-side.
- Use Tailwind utility classes for styling; no inline style objects.

## Testing

- Every new pure function in `lib/` gets a Vitest test in `tests/`.
- Run `npm test` before committing.

## Do not

- Do not add a database or auth unless explicitly requested (MVP is stateless).
- Do not introduce new dependencies without a clear reason.
- Do not commit `.env`, `.env.local`, or `node_modules`.
